Islamic State has built its own secure Android messaging app, according to a counter-terrorism network affiliated with the hacktivist group Anonymous. The app is reportedly being used to send encrypted messages regarding planned attacks.

The app, called Alrawi.apk, is being used by the terror group for communications and contains “encrypted communications features,” according to Ghost Security Group (GhostSec).

Both Alrawi.apk and the Amaq Agency app use the Android operating system, but are not available through the Google Play store. Instead, IS supporters must download the app\'s code in order to run it on their smartphones or tablets.

Prior to the newest two apps, IS was using the encrypted messaging app Telegram to distribute propaganda and recruit potential militants. Telegram says it has suspended over 660 IS-related accounts since November.

